Bombardment in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – Rhetoric has always been one of the main assets of American President Barack Obama.
It seems today, however, that his words have trapped him in a trap.
After having said last March that the United States "would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people" and mentioned last year a "red line" that should not be crossed, Obama will lose face if he does not react strongly to the murder, attributed to the Syrian regime, of more than 1000 civilians using sarin gas.
Of course, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why did Obama get stuck with such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line?
The American Secretary of State John Kerry is right to call the use of gas a "moral obscenity".
But torturing children, precursors of the civil war two years ago, is just as much.
And is killing civilians with chemical agents morally more obscene than bombing them, shooting at them, or letting them die of hunger?
It is commonly accepted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that some weapons are more immoral than others.
Mass destruction weapons, the nuclear bomb in particular, certainly cause more damage and more quickly than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing about 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb in Hiroshima and killing even more in a single night in Tokyo using incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas the Jews than to shoot them in mass graves?
One viewpoint, notably defended by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, suggests that a swift punitive action could convince Syrian President Bashar al-Assad to abandon the use of chemical weapons and return to "more mundane means to massacre his people."
In my opinion, this makes no sense.
The question is surely that of the massacre, not the methods used.
In any case, moral outrage, justified as it may be, is not a sufficient reason to go to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the death of more than 40 million Chinese in the 1950s and 1960s.
No sensible person has suggested that a military intervention in China was a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds – with the support of the United States.
Is this therefore a legal issue? The use of chemical weapons constitutes a factual violation of international conventions, including the Convention on the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, which Syria has never signed, and the Geneva Protocol, to which it is a party.
There are therefore valid reasons to consider Assad a war criminal, in which case he must be indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), established, by the way, by a treaty that the United States has never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not an easily defendable policy.
One could nevertheless argue that the "international community," or Western countries, or the United States as the main Western power, must surely draw a line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn away when innocent people are massacred?
Tolerating a genocide is not acceptable.
But exactly where should the line be drawn?
How many murders constitute a genocide?
Thousands?
Hundreds of thousands?
Millions?
Or is the number not even considered?
After all, genocide is a matter of intent, there is a will to kill or persecute individuals because of their race, ethnic affiliation or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for these reasons - or even two - would constitute a form of genocide.
The problem can be approached from another angle.
The question to consider before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance of improving the situation, saving lives, and making the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether through sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
Answering it involves asking: what is the best solution?
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
Just as the action of the ICC, "humanitarian intervention" is more likely to produce results in a weak country (for example Serbia, Mali or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a major power.
No one would consider missile strikes on China or Russia in the name of human rights defense or to enforce international norms and conventions relating to war.
Syria, as many have pointed out, is not Libya or Mali.
It is also not a major power.
But the civil war raging there has already spilled over its borders, involving more important countries, including Iran, Turkey and Russia.
There is no doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It is by no means certain that an American intervention would reduce the risk of a wider conflict.
In fact, some proponents of American intervention - both neoconservatives and "liberal hawks" - seem to desire the opposite: they long for a war with Iran.
And Obama has probably drawn a link in his mind between the red line regarding Syria and the one he has drawn for Iran, perhaps just as thoughtlessly, in order to prevent it from developing nuclear weapons.
What, then, should one expect from American strikes on Syrian targets, when Obama has already indicated that they are not intended to bring down the Syrian regime?
They will not end the civil war.
But a single missile would be enough to make the United States a direct participant in this war, causing a resurgence of violence.
Taking this risk to save Obama's honor does not seem particularly wise.
This viewpoint is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
This is the opinion of most Europeans.
And a majority of Americans.
It may even be Obama's opinion, which is why he is desperately trying to buy time by delegating to the American Congress the authorization for the use of military force in Syria.
Since his inauguration, his relations with Congress have been anything but easy.
But he needs it more than ever today to cover his back.
